english:
  title: Preface to the Presentation of the Tongguk Tonggam
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To govern is to prosper; to descend into chaos is to perish. In what has passed, we find our mirror for rise and fall. Without flattering words, without concealing faults—thus good and evil must be revealed to those who come after.

    Looking upon the rules of those who compiled histories, all took the annalistic form as their foundation. The Comprehensive Mirror had its beginning with Sima Guang of Pudu, casting off the tedium of the Records' biographical form. The Outline and Details was revealed through Zhu Xi of Huian, capturing the subtle meanings of praise and blame. The Minor Compendium followed in their way, creating a condensed version. Liu Yan wrote and composed its continuation. Though they differ in the fullness or brevity of their records, their structure and principles remain one.

    Consider that our Joseon has a nation, long called the land of culture and learning. Tangun stood equal to Yao of antiquity; the people grew pure and customs simple. Ki Ja received his fief from King Wu of Zhou; what passed transformed into spirit, what remained endured as legend. Yet how can empty words record what ancient texts do not verify? After the Four Commanderies were parceled out, after the Two Regions were torn asunder, the various Korean kingdoms swarmed forth and fell away. The Three Kingdoms stood in tripod arrangement, each carving out domains. Silla laid its foundation in the eastern lands, passing through three changes of dynasty while spanning the longest years. Goguryeo and Baekje both emerged from northern lands, two nations established with borders that met and touched. Yet each boasted of strength, each bragged of greatness, never ceasing their warfare, never befriending their neighbors. Time and again spears clashed, day by day the borderlands contracted. Examining rise and decline, we see differences in pace, yet judging success and failure, we find no distinction between them.

    Still, the national records barely survived, though their texts sometimes erred. Events bordered on the strange and unverified, language wandered without ground. Though the learned ones of former times revised and corrected them, yet they inherited the gaps and omissions of the original histories. Taebong brought itself to ruin; Taejo of Goryeo at last rose. Managing all directions, he defeated the competing lords and settled the realm. He subdued the two kingdoms, unified the three Hans into one house, establishing a majestic model for posterity, founding an enterprise to pass down through ages. Thirty rulers descended, inheriting through sons and grandsons, five hundred years witnessed, at times well-governed, at times troubled. The records exist complete—can merit and fault escape our sight?

    When the age of the former dynasty ended, the Mandate of Heaven passed to the true ruler. Our Taejo, the Kangheom Great King, grasped the tally of Heaven and initiated a new reign. Honoring antiquity, he elevated the civilizing arts. Following the example of Han's founder who collected Qin's documents, embodying Tang's emperor who acquired Sui's classics, he commanded that the histories of the fallen nation be sought out, filling the imperial treasury. When the Three Kings succeeded one another in reverent stewardship, promoting brilliant governance and achieving perfect order, they established the Historiographical Office, placing compilation under its charge. Thus the Complete History emerged, its collection comprehensive and all-encompassing. The Condensed Essentials came forth, refined and made concise. After many years, the work was completed—a great compilation of our age.

    Seong the Wise, the Great King of Virtue, carried virtue in his person and surpassed all in discernment. Focused and singular, he truly harmonized with Shun's wisdom and Yao's reverence. Great in his display, great in his inheritance, he pursued the cultural legacy of the Former Kings and the martial achievements of the Martial Kings. How lamentable that though our nation possessed ancient records, we had no long chronicle comparable to those of earlier masters. Just when we sought to draw forth these golden treasures, the realm passed to another.

    Humbly consider: the present sovereign has penetrated the deepest principles of governance, expanded the designs of previous rulers. His merit towers high, his writings shine brilliantly—through these the way of good government reaches its height. Continuing his predecessor's vision, recording his predecessor's deeds, the work shines forth with literary grace. The Comprehensive Mirror's completion comes perfectly in this age.

    We servants, bearing meager talents, received your command to compose this work. Our abilities lack the three excellences—how could mere words do justice to such a task? Desiring only to repay your great trust, we have exhausted our modest efforts. We gathered widely from many texts, compiled them into great volumes. Our precedents follow the Resource for Ruling; our principles truly embody the Spring and Autumn Annals. Following the sequence of years and months, we investigated each age and examined each event. Though we lack the skill of careful revision, we have sought to praise the good and censure the evil, fearing we fall short of the true art of the brush. Here and there we have ventured to add our own modest commentary, hoping to illuminate the right and wrong of ages past. From the highest to the lowest spans fourteen hundred years—let former failures become latter lessons. Gathered in fifty-six scrolls, our aim is rightness of principle and gravity of expression.

    Yet we fear we have only soiled your refined understanding, and shame weighs upon us. Should you place this beside you and read it in the quiet of night as you might survey the dynasties of Xia and Yin, may it become for ten thousand ages the mirror of governance.
